post_text: This year breakfast will look a little different in the MCS Cafeterias. Everything will be pre-packaged and available as a grab n go option for students to pick up just prior to the start of their school day. Students will then be able to take their breakfast with them back to their classroom where they can enjoy it there. We will still be serving both hot and cold options for breakfast and we encourage you to take a look at our fantastic breakfast menus! Breakfast this year will be $1.70 for paid students and $0.30 for reduced students. We are so excited to see your students again and can't wait to see their smiling faces!

post_text: With orientation and back to school nights being virtual this year, filling out a F/R app might seem impossible. Not with Titan though! You can fill out a F/R app online without even creating an account. See below for more details!
shared_text:
Middlebury Community Schools
August 4 at 9:34 AM ·

2020-2021 FREE AND REDUCED MEALS APPLICATIONS!
Previously, a paper application for Free and Reduced Price School Meals was sent home on the first day of school to all students. Now you can apply for free or reduced school meals online! The process is quick and easy, and in a few short steps you'll be done!
Parents can find the application online at the Titan Family Portal page https://family.titank12.com/.
You don't even have to log in to complete the application, you just have to simply select the Apply For Meals Today button.
On the next page, type Middlebury Community Schools in the district box and then complete the form and submit the application.

shared_text:
Middlebury Community Schools
June 2 at 9:17 AM ·

The Summer Food Service Program will be offering hot and cold meals to children 18 and younger during the summer break.
The program is federally funded through the U.S. Department of Agriculture with a goal of getting free or reduced-priced meals to students in need.
Below are the sites in both the Elkhart and Goshen School Districts that students can go to for a free meal during the summer. The students do not have to be eligible for free/reduced meals to eat. Any student can get a free meal up to the age of 18.

post_text: Today the 3rd Graders at JES had a very special lunch just for them as a way to say goodbye and we will miss you! All of the 3rd graders voted on their favorite entree, fruit, vegetable, and dessert. The winning option from each category was then placed on the menu today just for them. The winners were: cheesy flatbread pizza or beefy cheese nachos with fresh peppers/cucumbers, strawberries with whip cream, and an ice cream cup. Several 3rd graders even won prizes. Thank you for a great year! We will miss you!

post_text:
Do you and your students know everything they can get to make a reimbursable lunch? There are 5 possible components served at every lunch.
1. Whole grain-rich grain
2. Meat or Meat Alt (cheese/yogurt)
3. Fruit
4. Vegetable (cooked & fresh)
5. Low fat or fat free milk
Students can take foods from all 5 components to make their lunch, BUT THEY MUST TAKE AT LEAST 1/2 CUP OF A FRUIT OR VEGETABLE in order for it to be considered a reimbursable meal. They don't have to eat the fruit or vegetable if they do not want to once they get back to their seats or they can just take the entree and milk and be charged ala cart prices.
Pictured are examples of trays served at the K-5 buildings and the 6-12 buildings.

post_text:
This week we will be celebrating National School Breakfast Week. This week is brought to you by the School Nutrition Association. This week long celebration helps bring awareness to breakfast programs at schools around the nation.
Students who eat school breakfast are more likely to:
Reach higher levels of achievement in reading and math
Score higher on standardized tests
Have a better concentration and memory
Be more alert
Maintain a healthy weight

So take a week off in the kitchen and let us serve your student 😀🍳🥞🍇

post_text:
From our staff to you we wish you a very Merry Christmas and Happy New Year! Enjoy some of these fun Christmas facts while you enjoy time with family and friends today.
1. Candy Canes were used to keep children quite- requested by a choirmaster to keep children quite during church
2. Animal Crackers were originally a Christmas treat. Animal crackers were first introduced around Christmastime in 1902. The string on the box was originally intended to be used to hang the boxes on Christmas trees.
3. Fruit cake was intended to last all year- they were originally intended to be baked at the end of the harvest season and saved to be eaten at the beginning of the harvest season the following year, for good luck.
4. Turkey wasn't the main dish at Medieval Christmas feasts- but Peacock!
5. Christmas Dinner usually contains over 7,000 calories

post_text:
Today is National Sandwich Day. Here are some fun facts about Sandwiches:
1. The most popular sandwich in the USA is not PB&J actually, but surprisingly the plain ham sandwich, followed by a BLT.
2. John Montagu, the fourth Earl of Sandwich is credited with creating the first sandwich. Legend has it that he was unwilling to free up both hands during a 24 hour gambling event in order to eat. Instead, he asked his servant to put the meat from his meal between two slices of bread so he could hold it in one hand and continue gambling.
Sandwiches are a delicious way to incorporate a variety of food groups into one bite. Add some vegetables, meat and cheese between two slices of whole-grain bread and your stomach and heart will be happy! Enjoy a sandwich today 🥪😀

post_text: Today is National Eating Healthy Day. Take time today to get in that extra fruit or vegetable, piece of whole grain bread, or remove the skin off your chicken. If we take time everyday to make healthy choices, we will not only form healthy habits, but we will form a healthy, happy body.

post_text: Breakfast is THE most important meal of the day. It gives us the start we need to energize us through the day. Middlebury Community Schools serves breakfast every day at all 7 schools. Breakfast is served at the beginning of each school day in the cafeteria. The best part is, it is so affordable! Breakfast is $1.45 or $0.30 for those who qualify for reduced meals. If breakfast is not possible in the morning at your household, don't let your child fall behind in school, make sure they start off the day by stopping by the cafeteria for a nutritious and delicious breakfast.
